## Design decisions worth noting

| Decision | Rationale |
|---|---|
| **Timestamps stored as sorted array, pruned from front** | Appending is always O(1); pruning old entries is O(k) for k expired entries, amortised O(1) per request. Simpler and faster than a ring buffer or sorted set for typical `maxRequests` values (≤ a few hundred). |
| **`cleanupTimer.unref()`** | The cleanup interval is there for memory hygiene, not correctness. `unref()` means a process with no other live handles can exit without an explicit `close()` call — useful in tests and short-lived scripts. Production shutdowns should still call `close()` explicitly. |
| **`Retry-After` points to when the oldest slot expires** | This is the earliest moment a new request *could* succeed. It's more honest than `windowMs` (which would always overestimate for partially-consumed windows). |
| **`X-RateLimit-Reset` is epoch seconds** | Follows the de-facto standard used by GitHub, Twitter, and RFC 6585. Clients can compute `reset - Date.now()/1000` to know exactly how long to back off. |
| **No locking / mutex** | Node.js is single-threaded; the event loop serialises synchronous code, so the read-modify-write of the timestamps array is atomic within a single process. For multi-process deployments (e.g. PM2 cluster mode) you'd need a shared store such as Redis. |

